{"id":"1403.2305","submitter":"Shuang-Liang Li","authors":"Shuang-Liang Li, Mitchell C. Begelman","title":"Thermal stability of thin disk with magnetically driven winds","comments":"26 pages, 11 figures, accepted for publication in ApJ","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/0004-637X/786/1/6","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The absence of thermal instability in the high/soft state of black hole X-ray\nbinaries, in disagreement with the standard thin disk theory, is a\nlong-standing riddle for theoretical astronomers. We have tried to resolve this\nquestion by studying the thermal stability of a thin disk with magnetically\ndriven winds in the $\\dot{M}- \\Sigma$ plane. It is found that disk winds can\ngreatly decrease the disk temperature and thus help the disk become more stable\nat a given accretion rate. The critical accretion rate $\\dot{M}_{\\rm crit}$\ncorresponding to the thermal instability threshold is increased significantly\nin the presence of disk winds. For $\\alpha=0.01$ and $B_{\\rm \\phi}=10B_{\\rm\n_p}$, the disk is quite stable even for a very weak initial poloidal magnetic\nfield [$\\beta_{\\rm p,0}\\sim 2000, \\beta_{\\rm p}=(P_{\\rm {gas}}+P_{\\rm\nrad})/(B_{\\rm p}^2/8\\pi)$]. But when $B_{\\rm \\phi}=B_{\\rm _p}$ or $B_{\\rm\n\\phi}=0.1B_{\\rm _p}$, a somewhat stronger (but still weak) field ($\\beta_{\\rm\np,0}\\sim 200$ or $\\beta_{\\rm p,0}\\sim 20$) is required to make the disk stable.\nNevertheless, despite the great increase of $\\dot{M}_{\\rm crit}$, the\nluminosity threshold corresponding to instability remains almost constant or\neven decreases slowly with increasing $\\dot{M}_{\\rm crit}$ due to the decrease\nof gas temperature. The advection and diffusion timescales of the large-scale\nmagnetic field threading the disk are also investigated in this work. We find\nthat the advection timescale can be smaller than the diffusion timescale in a\ndisk with winds, because the disk winds take away most of the gravitational\nenergy released in the disk, resulting in the decrease of the magnetic\ndiffusivity $\\eta$ and the increase of the diffusion timescale.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Mar 2014 17:11:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-19"}
